[instrumental music]

00:55.881 --> 00:58.275
[music continues]

01:25.955 --> 01:28.436
[music continues]

01:56.158 --> 01:58.640
[music continues]

02:26.233 --> 02:28.757
[music continues]

02:56.350 --> 02:58.874
[music continues]

03:26.466 --> 03:28.991
[music continues]

03:44.398 --> 03:46.226
[thunder rumbling]

03:51.100 --> 03:52.841
[engine revving]

03:59.456 --> 04:02.242
[instrumental music]

04:15.080 --> 04:16.995
[dog barking]

04:28.529 --> 04:30.444
[indistinct chatter]

04:36.319 --> 04:37.842
Are they for us?

04:39.801 --> 04:41.455
No one said we can.

04:41.498 --> 04:43.761
No one said we can't,
though, right?

04:54.685 --> 04:56.121
[door opens]

04:56.165 --> 04:58.123
[instrumental music]

05:07.219 --> 05:08.525
May I have one?

05:14.618 --> 05:15.924
Thank you.

05:21.451 --> 05:24.454
Oh, that's lovely. Mm.

05:24.498 --> 05:27.588
It's a particularly good one.
Mm.

05:27.631 --> 05:30.242
Come on, everyone.
Come and get one.

05:30.286 --> 05:33.028
[instrumental music]

05:33.071 --> 05:34.508
[chuckles]

06:00.882 --> 06:03.580
My name is Roald Dahl.

06:03.624 --> 06:05.539
Now, some of you
may be wondering

06:05.582 --> 06:08.629
why there was a bowl
with peaches in it.

06:08.672 --> 06:10.021
Well, that's because

06:10.065 --> 06:13.068
I've written a book
about a peach.

06:13.111 --> 06:15.157
A magical one.

06:15.200 --> 06:19.335
And what I'm going to do today
is read you some of it.

06:19.379 --> 06:23.034
- Hey, what about this stone?
- Oh. Uh...

06:23.078 --> 06:28.082
Well... do you think you can
get it in the bowl from there?

06:28.126 --> 06:30.651
- Easy.
- Is it?

06:30.694 --> 06:33.393
Yes. Well, I tell you what...

06:35.351 --> 06:37.788
How about backwards, hmm?

06:40.748 --> 06:43.054
[indistinct chatter]

06:55.502 --> 06:57.895
[instrumental music]

07:08.384 --> 07:10.734
[indistinct chatter]

07:15.260 --> 07:17.175
Augustus.

07:17.219 --> 07:18.481
Dad.

07:20.091 --> 07:22.616
Caught the tail end.
Very amusing.

07:22.659 --> 07:24.400
- Thank you.
- Pete Perkins.

07:24.444 --> 07:26.576
- What is?
- Ah, that's my name.

07:26.620 --> 07:29.361
Is that so? Good for you.

07:29.405 --> 07:31.712
Consider myself a bit of
a wordsmith, actually.

07:31.755 --> 07:33.235
A few poems here and there.

07:33.278 --> 07:35.759
The odd colorful
limerick at university.

07:35.803 --> 07:37.848
That sort of thing.

07:37.892 --> 07:40.068
I definitely think
I've got a book or two in me.

07:41.678 --> 07:44.464
Not a children's book,
of course.

07:44.507 --> 07:45.900
Something a bit-- bit weightier.

07:45.943 --> 07:47.467
- Weightier?
- Mm.

07:47.510 --> 07:49.338
Well done for
"Johnny And The Giant..."

07:49.381 --> 07:51.340
- Pineapple.
- Ah, thank you, yes.

07:53.560 --> 07:55.736
"Johnny And The Giant
Pineapple." [laughs]

07:58.260 --> 07:59.609
We've all got to start
somewhere, haven't we?

07:59.653 --> 08:01.045
I did originally
think peach, but--

08:01.089 --> 08:02.960
No. No, no, no.

08:03.004 --> 08:04.919
Kids can relate to a pineapple.

08:04.962 --> 08:06.877
Pineapple's the one.

08:06.921 --> 08:08.966
I shall give you my card.

08:09.010 --> 08:10.751
If things pick up for you,

08:10.794 --> 08:14.015
you might need
a decent solicitor.

08:14.058 --> 08:15.843
I'm much more
than just a lawyer, you know.

08:15.886 --> 08:18.236
Dog with a bone,
that's what I am.

08:18.280 --> 08:20.761
And that's exactly
what someone like you needs.

08:20.804 --> 08:23.633
If I was your dog, with a bone,

08:23.677 --> 08:27.289
I would be 120 percent
committed to...

08:29.160 --> 08:32.163
I say. Isn't that...

08:32.207 --> 08:34.296
"Klaatu barada nikto."

08:34.338 --> 08:35.645
- Patricia Neal.
- Who?

08:35.688 --> 08:37.952
Oh, come on.
Patricia Neal. Huge.

08:37.995 --> 08:39.866
Great big American movie star.

08:39.909 --> 08:41.738
- How did she get here?
- What, transport-wise?

08:41.782 --> 08:44.393
No, no, what's she doing here
at this sorry little affair

08:44.436 --> 08:46.134
in the middle of nowhere?

08:46.177 --> 08:47.875
Probably the wrong address.
You know actresses.

08:47.918 --> 08:51.400
None too bright
but nice to look at.

08:51.443 --> 08:53.402
- Rather.
- Well, she's nothing special.

08:53.445 --> 08:56.797
The sort of girl I'd soon have
wrapped round my finger.

08:56.840 --> 08:59.451
- In your dreams, old chap.
- Oh, really?

08:59.495 --> 09:02.846
I don't know if you're a
betting man, Mr. Perkins,

09:02.890 --> 09:08.199
but ten bob says that I leave
with Patricia Neal tonight.

09:08.243 --> 09:11.768
Okay. I'll take your money.

09:11.812 --> 09:13.640
Gus can be banker.

09:19.733 --> 09:21.996
Ms. Neal, allow me
to introduce myself.

09:22.039 --> 09:23.606
I'm Roald Dahl.

09:23.650 --> 09:25.695
- The Roald Dahl?
- One and the same.

09:25.739 --> 09:28.350
And this is my good friend,
Jerry Jenkins.

09:28.393 --> 09:30.613
Well, it's lovely
to meet you, Mr. Jenkins.

09:30.657 --> 09:32.746
Perkins, actually.
Pete Perkins.

09:32.789 --> 09:34.356
I'm sorry. I knew it was
something along those lines.

09:34.399 --> 09:36.097
And this is Gus.
Augustus, really.

09:36.140 --> 09:37.838
But he prefers Gus.
Don't you, Gus?

09:37.881 --> 09:41.102
- Pleasure to meet you, Gus.
- Wow.

09:41.145 --> 09:43.626
Funny thing, Patricia, if I may.

09:43.670 --> 09:45.454
Pete here's just bet me
ten shillings

09:45.497 --> 09:47.717
that I don't leave with you
tonight.

09:50.024 --> 09:52.200
Leave with me, as in...

09:52.243 --> 09:54.550
Well, Mr. Jenkins, really.

09:54.594 --> 09:55.899
- It wasn't my...
- Oh, come now.

09:55.943 --> 09:57.335
Didn't you just say
that actresses are

09:57.379 --> 10:00.382
none too bright
but nice to look at?

10:00.425 --> 10:02.906
- No, you just said that...
- So, how about it, Pat?

10:02.950 --> 10:05.517
I've a nice little place
the other side of Amersham.

10:05.561 --> 10:08.608
Well, Mr. Dahl,
I'm flattered by your offer,

10:08.651 --> 10:11.959
but well, I'm not sure
my husband would approve.

10:12.002 --> 10:14.831
Oh. You're married.
What a shame.

10:14.875 --> 10:18.008
Although I have to say, I am a
bit of a sucker for a tall man.

10:18.052 --> 10:19.314
Well, that's a bit of luck.

10:19.357 --> 10:20.750
Any other qualities
you look for?

10:20.794 --> 10:24.058
Well, let me think, now...

10:24.101 --> 10:27.365
There is one thing
I can't resist.

10:27.409 --> 10:30.064
That's a man who cooks
a good breakfast.

10:30.107 --> 10:33.415
Well, Ms. Neal, I have to tell
you that back in Great Missenden

10:33.458 --> 10:35.286
they call me
the King of Breakfasts.

10:35.330 --> 10:39.682
- Oh, do they, now?
- Hey. What about your husband?

10:39.726 --> 10:42.424
[whispers]
I won't tell him if you don't.

10:42.467 --> 10:44.078
So good to have met you, Gus.

10:44.121 --> 10:46.036
- No, no. All yours.
- Mr. Jenkins.

10:46.080 --> 10:47.472
Jerry.

10:53.261 --> 10:56.003
You, Mr. Dahl,
are one big kid.

10:56.046 --> 10:57.657
Is that so?

10:57.700 --> 11:01.008
And the day you stop
is the day I file for divorce.

11:04.794 --> 11:07.231
[instrumental music]

11:11.366 --> 11:15.196
Roald: We had two daughters.
The first we called Olivia.

11:15.239 --> 11:17.372
Olivia Twenty Dahl.

11:17.415 --> 11:19.417
Olivia from Twelfth Night.

11:19.461 --> 11:21.855
Twenty because that's all
the money I had in my pocket

11:21.898 --> 11:24.684
on the bright sunny day
she was born.

11:24.727 --> 11:28.557
Olivia. Our little zookeeper.

11:28.600 --> 11:31.516
Then there was
Chantal Sophia Dahl.

11:31.560 --> 11:33.040
Sophia after my mother.

11:33.083 --> 11:36.478
But we realized
she'd be Chantal Dahl.

11:36.521 --> 11:38.828
So she became Tessa.

11:38.872 --> 11:41.396
Tessa who always agreed
the best approach

11:41.439 --> 11:43.485
was to do things her own way,

11:43.528 --> 11:45.530
including sleeping
anywhere she could,

11:45.574 --> 11:48.751
so long as
it wasn't in her bed.

11:48.795 --> 11:51.145
And Theo,
the boy who we nearly lost

11:51.188 --> 11:52.712
in a traffic accident

11:52.755 --> 11:55.627
on a wet winter road
in New York City.

11:57.455 --> 12:00.763
Then, of course, Pat,
star of stage and screen.

12:00.807 --> 12:03.853
Now trying to keep her career
and her family afloat

12:03.897 --> 12:07.161
in a rickety old tub
we called Gipsy House.

12:08.336 --> 12:10.251
[instrumental music]

12:12.253 --> 12:14.385
And then we come in to land.

12:16.039 --> 12:17.780
[dog barks]

12:24.874 --> 12:27.094
Gabriel's wing's better now.

12:27.137 --> 12:29.357
It is, isn't it?

12:29.400 --> 12:32.403
He's not Gabriel.
He's Uriel.

12:32.447 --> 12:34.405
Do you call them
all after angels?

12:34.449 --> 12:36.146
They are all angels.

12:36.190 --> 12:39.193
Angels that shit everywhere,
that's for sure.

12:39.236 --> 12:40.498
Come on.

12:40.542 --> 12:42.979
[instrumental music]

12:43.023 --> 12:44.633
Roald: And his name
is Charlie Rocket.

12:44.676 --> 12:46.983
Olivia: Daddy, I love that
you call him that.

12:47.027 --> 12:49.333
Roald: He lives in a little
house with his mother and father

12:49.377 --> 12:50.900
and his father's
mother and father

12:50.944 --> 12:52.641
and his mother's
mother and father.

12:52.684 --> 12:55.383
Olivia: All in one house?
Roald: All in one bed.

12:55.426 --> 12:59.430
They're very poor, you see.
Poor and all called Bob.

12:59.474 --> 13:01.128
- All called Bob?
- Yes.

13:01.171 --> 13:02.912
Both grandmothers
are called Roberta.

13:02.956 --> 13:06.916
Then there's Grandpa Robert
and other Grandpa Robert.

13:06.960 --> 13:11.442
- [chuckles] That's funny.
- I don't know. It might work.

13:11.486 --> 13:15.142
- What sweets do they make?
- Oh, incredible ones.

13:15.185 --> 13:16.970
Fudge?
Can there be fudge?

13:17.013 --> 13:18.972
Oh, yes, there'll be
a whole lake of it.

13:19.015 --> 13:20.843
And gobstoppers?

13:20.887 --> 13:22.627
Oh, yes, they're your favorite,
aren't they?

13:22.671 --> 13:25.456
Yeah, but they never
last long enough.

13:25.500 --> 13:26.980
These ones will.

13:27.023 --> 13:29.809
In fact,
these will last forever.

13:29.852 --> 13:31.680
[instrumental music]

13:31.723 --> 13:35.640
He's the PT Barnum
of confectionery.

13:35.684 --> 13:38.121
He made a palace entirely
out of chocolate

13:38.165 --> 13:41.385
for a maharajah once.

13:41.429 --> 13:42.909
Prince Pilau.

13:42.952 --> 13:45.128
No.

13:45.172 --> 13:47.652
Prince Peeperpeepoo.

13:47.696 --> 13:50.525
No. Probably not that either.

13:50.568 --> 13:53.180
It'll come to me. Mm?

14:01.623 --> 14:03.930
[instrumental music]

14:07.324 --> 14:08.760
Careful.

14:16.594 --> 14:19.206
I don't know
why you like it so much.

14:19.249 --> 14:21.338
It's a shivery smile.

14:22.949 --> 14:24.559
Roald: A shivery smile.

14:34.177 --> 14:36.136
The other thing
that our man likes

14:36.179 --> 14:40.618
is to make fountains
out of sugar.

14:40.662 --> 14:42.838
The trouble is
it gets a bit sticky.

14:42.882 --> 14:45.275
[indistinct radio chatter]

14:52.674 --> 14:54.719
When's Livvy going to be home?

14:54.763 --> 14:56.678
They won't be too much longer,
darling.

14:56.721 --> 14:58.680
Go find something
and play until they get back.

14:58.723 --> 15:00.377
But I've played everything.

15:00.421 --> 15:02.466
Well, you can't have
played everything.

15:02.510 --> 15:04.816
I have. Really.

15:04.860 --> 15:06.470
Now, do you remember
what mommy said

15:06.514 --> 15:08.211
about having to work?

15:08.255 --> 15:10.648
Uh-huh, and I was
only to disturb you

15:10.692 --> 15:12.128
if it was an emergency.

15:12.172 --> 15:14.000
- That's right.
- Like now.

15:16.959 --> 15:20.093
And what is the emergency?

15:20.136 --> 15:22.312
Your feet are on fire.
Come on.

15:25.489 --> 15:28.231
Patricia: Pixies are sneaky
as gannets, they are.

15:28.275 --> 15:31.365
Do all sorts, they do,
when folk got their back turned.

15:31.408 --> 15:36.848
But the thing about pixies,
they go mi-mi-mi-mi-mi...

15:36.892 --> 15:39.025
But right quiet, like, so you
gotta keep

15:39.068 --> 15:41.853
a lughole peeled to 'ear 'em.

15:41.897 --> 15:43.725
Why are you talking like that?

15:43.768 --> 15:46.510
- Mommy's practicing, darling.
- What's all this?

15:46.554 --> 15:48.686
We're looking for pixies.

15:48.730 --> 15:50.993
Pixies?
In Buckinghamshire?

15:51.037 --> 15:54.692
Fat chance. No, you only get
pixies in Cornwall.

15:54.736 --> 15:57.173
- But mummy said...
- Well, silly mummy.

15:57.217 --> 15:59.567
And, daddy, daddy is right.

15:59.610 --> 16:02.439
In Buckinghamshire
we get fairies.

16:02.483 --> 16:05.268
- Fairies! We've got fairies.
- Well, yes, that's right.

16:05.312 --> 16:07.227
But the trouble with fairies,
you see,

16:07.270 --> 16:09.185
is-- is they're terribly shy,

16:09.229 --> 16:10.882
and so it's quite hard
to see them.

16:10.926 --> 16:14.930
Yes. Unless it's the third
of November, of course.

16:14.974 --> 16:16.366
When's that?

16:18.325 --> 16:20.936
Well, how-- how incredible.
That's today.

16:20.980 --> 16:22.329
What are the chances?

16:22.372 --> 16:25.636
And today is
Bubbalubbadumdum Day.

16:25.680 --> 16:27.247
What's Bubba-lubble Day?

16:27.290 --> 16:30.337
Bubbalubbadumdum Day is
the day that Oppletopple,

16:30.380 --> 16:33.209
king of the fairies, uh,

16:33.253 --> 16:35.690
leads a parade on a,
on a big black rabbit.

16:35.733 --> 16:38.432
- Like Trilby.
- Exactly like Trilby.

16:38.475 --> 16:40.651
Can we see it?

16:40.695 --> 16:43.741
Oh, well, now, let me think.

16:45.569 --> 16:47.006
Hey, darling.

16:49.008 --> 16:50.705
- Nothing yet?
- Oh, no.

16:50.748 --> 16:54.013
Both: Mummy, daddy, come and
see! Come and see! Quickly!

16:54.056 --> 16:55.623
Alright, alright.
Daddy will come.

16:55.665 --> 16:57.929
Mummy's got to take an
important call about a part.

17:00.367 --> 17:02.021
Well, well.

17:03.805 --> 17:06.589
Do you think
King Appleflapple will like it?

17:06.634 --> 17:10.855
Oppletopple? Of course he will.
It's magnificent.

17:10.898 --> 17:12.770
Can we see him on his rabbit?

17:12.814 --> 17:15.208
Well, as long as
it's not past bath time.

17:15.251 --> 17:17.036
Oh, dear. Which it is.

17:17.079 --> 17:20.778
But, daddy, you said we
could if we made a tribble.

17:20.821 --> 17:24.260
- Tribute.
- So can we?

17:24.304 --> 17:26.132
We'll have to see
in the morning. Mm?

17:28.656 --> 17:31.137
This isn't one of
your stories, is it?

17:35.228 --> 17:36.577
You'll see.

17:46.108 --> 17:48.067
Come on. I'm gonna get you!

17:50.156 --> 17:51.679
No, you aren't.

17:53.985 --> 17:55.987
No, come here!

17:56.031 --> 18:00.427
Livvy, I said not red ones.
Mommy has to pay those.

18:00.470 --> 18:01.950
Sorry.

18:06.172 --> 18:07.564
Is that what you want?

18:07.608 --> 18:09.131
You want them to fly away,
do you, Livvy?

18:09.175 --> 18:10.480
They'd come back.

18:10.524 --> 18:12.178
Well, I admire your optimism.

18:12.221 --> 18:14.354
They will. It's their home.

18:17.879 --> 18:19.881
Go and run your bath, will you?

18:25.321 --> 18:27.671
I'm withering on the vine here.

18:29.108 --> 18:31.153
- Darling...
- Don't.

18:32.459 --> 18:35.375
They say who they're going with?

18:35.418 --> 18:37.116
Rachel Roberts.

18:37.159 --> 18:39.683
Got the right sort of
earthiness to her, I suppose.

18:39.727 --> 18:40.728
And I don't?

18:40.771 --> 18:41.990
They're just used to seeing you

18:42.033 --> 18:44.166
in a fox fur
drinking a martini.

18:44.210 --> 18:46.125
What does that mean?
It's all I'm good for?

18:46.168 --> 18:48.214
- That's not what I'm saying.
- It doesn't matter.

18:48.257 --> 18:51.391
I've, I've still got that
crappy airport thing.

18:51.434 --> 18:54.089
Well, like I said, don't do it
if you don't want to.

18:54.133 --> 18:58.137
That is ripe coming from
the man whose last advance

18:58.180 --> 19:00.356
wouldn't even cover a
case of that Scotch

19:00.400 --> 19:01.966
you're always so
fond of downing.

19:02.010 --> 19:03.185
My writing pays.

19:03.229 --> 19:04.665
It would
pay a hell of a lot more

19:04.708 --> 19:06.710
if you weren't so bloody-minded.

19:06.754 --> 19:08.103
What's that supposed to mean?

19:08.147 --> 19:13.543
It means,
kids want Enid Blyton.

19:13.587 --> 19:17.199
Not the twisted crap
that comes out of your head.

19:17.243 --> 19:18.592
Oh, sod you, Pat.

19:18.635 --> 19:20.289
I was only bloody
trying to be nice.

19:27.253 --> 19:29.603
[instrumental music]

19:34.260 --> 19:35.783
You can shut up.

19:57.413 --> 19:59.763
[music continues]

20:26.007 --> 20:30.403
Now, now... where were we?

20:30.446 --> 20:33.406
- Chapter five.
- Ah.

20:33.449 --> 20:35.973
Yes, the river of marshmallow.

20:38.976 --> 20:42.110
You're going to drink all that?

20:42.153 --> 20:44.286
You're starting to
sound like our mother.

